AVIAN INFLUENZA (57): RUSSIA (TUVA) HPAI H5, WILD BIRD, OIE
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 17 Jun 2016
Source: OIE, WAHID weekly disease information 2016; 29(25) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=20335


Highly pathogenic avian influenza, Russia
-----------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 17 Jun 2016 from Dr Evgeny Nepoklonov, Deputy Head, Federal Service for Veterinary and Phytosanitary Surveillance, Ministry of Agriculture, Moscow, Russia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 9 Jun 2016
Date of confirmation of the event: 9 Jun 2016
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 6 Aug 2015
Manifestation of disease: sub-clinical infection
Causal agent: highly pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H5
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic and advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Ubsu-Nur, Ovyursky, Respublika Tyva [Tuva]
Date of start of the outbreak: 9 Jun 2016
Outbreak status: resolved 15 Jun 2016
Epidemiological unit: not applicable
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Grey Heron: _Ardea cinerea_ (Ardeidae) / - / 4 / 0 / 4 / 0
Great crested grebe: _Podiceps cristatus_ (Podicipedidae) / - / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0
Black-headed gull: _Larus ridibundus_ (Laridae) / - / 6 / 0 / 6 / 0
Common tern: _Sterna hirundo_ (Laridae) / - / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0
Great Cormorant:_Phalacrocorax carbo_ (Phalacrocoracidae_) / - / 4 / 0 / 4 / 0
_Anatidae_ (unidentified): _Anatidae_ (incognita)(_Anatidae_): / - / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: contact with wild species
Epidemiological comments: during the active monitoring of the ornithofauna in the surroundings of Ubsu-Nur Lake, a few wild birds were shot. Genome of H5 avian influenza virus was detected in 17 samples from carcasses of birds [black-headed gull (_Larus ridibundus_), grey heron (_Ardea cinerea_), common tern (_Sterna hirundo_), great crested grebe (_Podiceps cristatus_), great cormorant (_Phalacrocorax carbo_), duck (_Anatidae_). Sequence analysis of the isolates showed that they belonged to the Asian HPAI virus H5 lineage A/Guangdong/1/96, clade 2.3.4.4.

Control measures
Measures applied: control of wildlife reservoirs, screening, no vaccination, no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: All-Russian Research Institute for Animal Health (FGBI-ARRIAH) (national laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
_Anatidae_ (unidentified) / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Black-headed gull / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Common Tern / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Great cormorant / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Great crested grebe / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Grey Heron / virus sequencing / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
_Anatidae_ (unidentified) / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Black-headed gull / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Common tern / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Great cormorant / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Great crested grebe / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive
Grey heron / real-time reverse transcriptase / polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 9 Jun 2016 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

